<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">The Animal Welfare movement acknowledges the suffering of nonhumans and attempts to reduce that suffering through "humane" treatment, but it does not have as a goal elimination of the use and exploitation of animals. The Animal Rights movement goes significantly further by rejecting the exploitation of animals and according them rights in that regard. A person committed to animal welfare might be concerned that cows get enough space, proper food, etc., but would not necessarily have any qualms about killing and eating cows, so long as the rearing and slaughter are "humane". The Animal Welfare movement is represented by such organizations as the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, and the Humane Society. Having said this, it should be realized that</span>**__some hold a broad__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">er</span> **__interpretation of the__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> AR </span>**__[Animal Rights] movement.__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> They would argue that the AW groups do, in fact, support rights for animals (e.g., a dog has the right not to be kicked).</span>**__Under this interpretation,__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> AR</span>**__[Animal Rights] is__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> viewed as </span>**__a broad umbrella covering the__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> AW</span>**__[Animal Welfare] and strict__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> AR</span>**__[Animal Rights] groups. This interpretation has the advantage of moving__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> AR </span>**__[Animal Rights] closer to the mainstream.__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">Nevertheless, there is a valid distinction between the animal welfare and animal rights groups, as described in the first paragraph.</span>

Further, prefer the broad interpretation of animal rights because it creates clear grounds for conflict on the topic. The aff defends that animals are due respect, and the neg defends that they are not. A more strict interpretation of animal rights would allow the negative to side-step the central question of the topic entirely by simply agreeing that animals matter and arguing that they should be respected in a different way than having rights, such as advocating animal welfare.
