**First**, the affirmative burden is not to justify rights for all species of the kingdom Animalia, only highly developed macro-organisms. __Waldau 11__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">[[file:///C:/Users/User/Documents/Past%20Years/Animal%20Rights/Aff/Reductionism%20AC3.docx#_ftn1|[1]]]</span>

<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">Nonetheless, given that science reveals that so much of “life” is micro, or inaccessible to humans, claims about humans protecting “all animals” or “all life” need to be understood in context. Otherwise, they will seem a serious overstatement, because the goal of protecting “all animals” is, it turns out, no simple matter.</span> __For all practical purposes, the focus of animal protectionists from ancient time until today has been macro forms of life that we can easily identify. These include most mammals, some birds, and certain reptiles like turtles, but often not fish and certainly not__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> many of </span>__the micro forms__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> that are </span>__impossible to notice without the aid of a microscope__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> or other technology. The invisible forms of life that science has been so diligent in indentifying may constantly surround us, but we simple are not the kind of beings who can factor protecting them into our daily lives. Importantly, there are indications in our daily language that we take this into account, for while talk about killing animals is so morally charged that it regularly elicits challenges, talk about “killing germs” or using antibiotics (literally, “against life”) does not.</span>

Prefer this interpretation because it best adheres to historical usage and topic literature, which are the source of ground on the topic and thus key to fair and educational debate.

**Second**, rights are general side constraints on treatment, but they need not be absolute.
__Kamm 07__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">[[file:///C:/Users/User/Documents/Past%20Years/Animal%20Rights/Aff/Reductionism%20AC3.docx#_ftn2|[2]]]</span>

<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">However,</span>__the concept of a right need not imply that respecting a right will always take precedence over the greater good__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> (either at the act or the rule level).</span>__Rights need not be absolute, but rather__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">, may</span>__have thresholds beyond which the calculation of goods and evils is reintroduced.__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">37 I may have a right that you give me something, but if a great good is possible only by transgressing my right, this may be permitted. In such a case, the right will have been infringed rather than violated. The more good we must sacrifice rather than transgress the right, the more stringent is the right by at least one measure. It has been claimed that some fundamental human rights are stringent enough to stand in the way of even great goods, whose achievement they prevent. This may be because the rights represent the worth of the person, which is the presupposition of the importance of promoting interests. But rights can also conflict with the personal interests of agents who have to act in accord with them.</span>

Prefer this interpretation because it is most consistent with common usage. We talk of a right to free speech even though it can sometimes be restricted, and a right to property, even though property can be seized in certain instances.

Third, the aff burden is not to defend that rights are good in-and-of themselves because no moral theory defends this. Deontology says rights good as a means of respecting persons, and contractarianism says rights are good as a means of increasing self-interest. Therefore, my burden is only to defend that rights are instrumentally good to some higher goal of justice.


**Fourth**, the resolution is a general principle, so discussion of particular animal rights policies has no bearing on it. Specification is unfeasible because there are no practical limits on the topic, and holding the aff to the standard of categorical proof skews burdens vastly in favor of the negative. Only a general principle ensures reciprocity.

