<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">Even more important and certainly more generally applicable is the argument from queerness.</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">If there were objective values, then they would be</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">entities or</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">qualities</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">or relations</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">of a very strange sort,</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">utterly</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">different from everything else in the universe. Correspondingly, if we were aware of them, it would have to be by some special faculty</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> or moral perception or intuition, utterly</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">different from our ordinary ways of knowing everything else. When we ask the awkward question, how we can be aware of the truth of values, none of our ordinary accounts of sensory perception</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> or introspection or the framing and confirming of explanatory hypotheses or inference or logical construction or conceptual analysis, or any combination of these,</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">will provide a satisfactory answer;</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> ‘a special sort of intuition’ is a lame answer, but it is the one to which the clear-headed objectivist is compelled to resort.</span>

<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">Moreover, the possibility of objective value is empirically disproven by the fact that no one can agree on what it is.</span>

**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">Mackie-2</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">[[file:///C:/Users/User/Documents/Past%20Years/Animal%20Rights/Neg/NCs/Contractarianism%20NC%204.0.docx#_ftn2|[2]]]</span>

**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">The argument from relativity has as its premises the well-known variation of moral codes from one society to another and from one period to another,</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> and also the differences between different groups and classes within a complex community. Such variation is in itself merely a truth of descriptive morality, a fact of anthropology which entails neither first order nor second order ethical views. Yet it may indirectly support subjectivism: </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">radical differences between</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> first order </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">moral judgments make it difficult to treat those judgments as apprehensions of objective truths…</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">In short, the argument from relativity has some force simply because </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">the</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">actual </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">variations in</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">the </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">moral codes are more readily </span>__****__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">explained by</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> the hypothesis that they reflect </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">different ways of life than by</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> the hypothesis that they express </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">perceptions</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">, most of them seriously inadequate and badly distorted, </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">of objective values. </span>__**

<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">Therefore, justice cannot be grounded in any objective sense of right and wrong. </span>



<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">This creates a dilemma because any moral system not grounded in moral truths would seem to be arbitrary and give persons no reason to adhere to it. Only self-interested contractarianism escapes this dilemma: we follow moral rules because it is in our mutual self-interest to do so. </span>

<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">David **__Gauthier__** explains[[file:///C:/Users/User/Documents/Past%20Years/Animal%20Rights/Neg/NCs/Contractarianism%20NC%204.0.docx#_ftn3|[3]]]</span>

<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">Morals by agreement begin from an initial presumption against morality, as a constraint on each person's pursuit of his own interest. </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">A person</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> is conceived as an independent centre of activity, endeavoring to direct his capacities and resources to the fulfillment of his interests. He considers what he can do, but </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">initially d</span>__****__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">raws no distinction between what he may and may not do.</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> How then does he come to acknowledge the distinction? How does a person come to recognize a moral dimension to choice, if morality is not initially present? Morals by agreement offer a contractarian rationale for distinguishing what one may and may not do. </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">Moral principles are introduced as the objects of </span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">fully </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">voluntary</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> ex ante </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">agreement among rational persons.</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">Such agreement is hypothetical, in supposing a pre-moral context for the adoption of moral rules and practices. But the parties to agreement are real, determinate individuals, distinguished by their capacities, situations, and concerns. </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">In so far as they would agree to constraints on their choices</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">, restraining their pursuit of their own interests, </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">they acknowledge a distinction between what they may and may not do.</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">As rational persons understanding the structure of their interaction, </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">they recognize a place for mutual constraint, and so for a moral dimension in their affairs.</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> That there is a contractarian rationale for morality must of course be shown. That is the task of our theory. Here our immediate concern is to relate the idea of such a rationale to the introduction of fundamental moral distinctions. This is not a magical process. Morality does not emerge as the rabbit from the empty hat. Rather, as we shall argue, it emerges quite simply from the application of the maximizing conception of rationality to certain structures of interaction: Agreed mutual constraint is the rational response to these structures. Reason overrides the presumption against morality. </span>

<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">Therefore, the criterion is adhering to mutually self-interested agreements.</span>




<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">I contend that contractarianism would not give weight to animal rights.</span>

<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">First, animals lack the capacity to engage in contractarian agreements. </span>

<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">Jan **__Narveson__** writes<span style="font-size: 12pt;">[[file:///C:/Users/User/Documents/Past%20Years/Animal%20Rights/Neg/NCs/Contractarianism%20NC%204.0.docx#_ftn4|[4]]]</span></span>

<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">But consider rational beings. Figuring out what it would be rational for them to do is useful, because being rational, there is a pretty significant probability that they will do what it is rational for them to do. Hence it will be well to deal with them as rational beings; and this, as we have painfully learned and are still learning, drives us rather strongly in the direction of what we presently call "morality", that is, a set of restrictions on our behavior which are not just reactions to immediate threat or prospect of short-term obvious gain, but rather, broad-gauged, long-term commitments to certain patterns of behavior provided that the others generally speaking conform as well. These commitments are, then, the product of self-interest and are very like (and in many cases explicitly are) agreements. Now here is where rights are something substantial to found "oughts", and are not mere restatements of "ought" propositions from, as it were, the other end. </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">To talk of "rights"</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> here</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">is to talk of</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> the basis of </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">claims which we have self-interested reason to make</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> and do make, in varying ways; </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">and the reason</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> for </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">others</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> to </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">concede these rights to us is that they have an interest in our respecting</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> them </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">[their rights]</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> in their case, an interest </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">which rationally induces them to close the deal,</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> as it were, and commit themselves to paying the price of respecting them in our case. </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">No such basis of morality is</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">, however, </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">available for beings which cannot make this kind of</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> claims and </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">commitment</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">s, that is, for beings which, whatever interest they may have in coming in for these benefits, simply do not have the sort of rational equipment which would enable them to pose the right kind of threat if we don't, or to make the advantages of our extending these rights conditional upon their accepting similar limitations. </span>
<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">[…]</span>
<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">Now,</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">this perspective puts animals out of the reach of morality without</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> at all </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">denying that they are capable of suffering</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">, etc. Instead, it provides the basis for a frank, and of course heartless, rejection of the relevance of their sufferings. In this resFGpect, it is simply non-Kantian and non-(classical) utilitarian. </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">There is plenty of room</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> within it </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">to argue</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;">, say, that we would be better people if we did respect animals, or </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">that animals are really quite lovable and</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> we </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">would do better</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> to treat them </span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">as pets</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> than as potential meals, and so on.</span>**__<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">But none of this will get us to animal rights, as part of the fundamental apparatus of morality.</span>__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 6pt;"> What I am saying here, then, is that egoism seems to give a coherent and quite theoretically smooth account of our moral intuitions and of our attitudes about animals which preserves the latter rather than rejecting them. Or, more guardedly, what I should say is that if the apparent difficulties with egoism can be solved, then it does this; and I am far less certain that those difficulties cannot be solved than I once was. Obviously, one has the alternative of judging that if we have to go to the length of embracing this nasty doctrine in order to salvage our affection for filet mignon, then that is just all the more reason for giving up the filthy habit. I don't propose to try to resolve that one in this article. But at any rate, I hope it will by now be apparent that this question about the moral status of animals being one of the real watershed issues of moral philosophy has been amply confirmed. </span>




<span style="font-family: Georgia,serif; font-size: 12pt;">Second, even if animals could engage in contractarian agreements, humans would have no reason to submit to them since animals have no counter-balancing benefit to offer. For example, factory farmers have no reason to constrain their practices toward livestock, since their farms will run equally well with or without animals’ consent.</span>

