(Saint James)
The **value** is **justice**, defined as giving each their due. Justice is distinct from morality because morality focuses on what one ought to do, while justice focuses on what one deserves. For example, while it may be morally praiseworthy to donate to charity, it cannot be said that justice requires that you donate to charity because the poor are not entitled to the fruits of your labor.

Therefore, to clarify what people are entitled to, I tender the **criterion** of **reciprocity**. The obligation to do to others as they have done to you is what separates deserved reward or punishment from undeserved.

This criterion is best for 3 reasons:

**First**, reciprocity is the nearly universally accepted standard for justice. Almost all religions contain some form of the golden rule, and almost every legal system, from Hammurabi’s Code to the US criminal justice system, is based on punishment proportional to crime.

**Second**, reciprocity is intuitively the basis for justice. For example, it is the reason why we would not punish someone for failing to donate money but would punish them for failing to return money that had been lent to them. In one case, the recipient had a reciprocal claim to the money; in the other, they didn’t.

**Third**, reciprocity gives people a reason to be just. If you did not expect others to treat you based on how you treat them, then you would have little practical incentive to treat others fairly. Only reciprocity provides such an incentive. Professor of philosophy at the University of Alabama (Roll Tide!), James __Rachels__, furthers[[file:///C:/Users/User/Documents/Past%20Years/Animal%20Rights/Neg/NCs/Reciprocity%20NC.docx#_ftn1|[1]]]

<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">To these reasons a third may be added. Morality includes (some would say it consists in) how we choose to treat other people in our myriad interactions with them. But if reciprocity could not be expected, the morality of treating others well would come to occupy a less important place in people’s lives. In a system that respects deserts,</span> __someone who treats others well may expect to be treated well in return, while someone who treats others badly cannot. If this aspect of moral life were eliminated, morality would have no reward, and__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">immoralitywouldhavenobadconsequence;so</span>__there would be less reason__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> for one </span>__to be concerned with it.__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> If people were perfectly benevolent, of course, such incentives would not be needed. But for imperfectly benevolent beings such as us the acknowledgment of deserts</span> __[This] provides the reason for being moral that is required for the__<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> whole</span> __system to be effective.__

Therefore, my sole **contention** is that reciprocity does not require animal rights.

Animals cannot understand the concept of human rights, and even if they could, they would not respect our rights, as their primary concern is their own survival and well-being. There is therefore no more reason to value a lion’s rights than the rights of someone who is attempting to murder you, as both place the same value on your life, namely a value of 0. Moreover, even if we did have some obligation to animals, that obligation would not be to provide rights, as animals cannot understand or utilize their rights. Rights are therefore useless to animals, and focusing on animal welfare instead would be preferable in such a case. Thus, you should negate.

