<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;">In addition to these legal authorizations for the legitimate use of lethal force,</span> **__the U.S.__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> also </span>**__needs to extend the successful targeted killing policy that is being used in Afghanistan and Pakistan, to Somalia__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> and Yemen. Under this policy, expanded recently by the Obama administration, targeted strikes are conducted by drones and missiles against al Qaeda and Taliban leaders. They are permissible under international law. The targeted killing strategy must be used to hit pirates in Somalia—when they set off from Somali shores to hijack ships, and more easily when they return with ransom money. This is the only way forward. It is regrettable that</span> **__the failure of the legal system__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> to bring pirates to justice effectively </span>**__has created a perverse incentive to kill rather than prosecute.__**<span style="color: #a6a6a6; font-size: 6pt;"> Until Somalia has a legal system capable of convicting pirates, </span>**__killing them is the only option.__**


